ce:section.ce:para:
The ASH-CQDs were prepared with and without surface passivation by simple one-step hydrothermal method (Scheme 1
                        ). All the three formulations that were synthesized were brownish yellow in color when observed in day light and blue under UV light. The optical properties were stable and intact for a period of one year. The absorption bands of NCQDs were characterised by UV–vis spectrophotometry, which revealed two absorption band widths. HASHP showed characteristic absorption at 278 nm and 344 nm; HASHNH3 absorption at 285 nm and 338 nm, HASHEDA absorption at 284 nm and 335 nm. The first bandwidth between 270 and 290 nm denotes the π-π* electron transition of CC bonds of sp2 domain and the second bandwidth between 320 and 390 nm reflected the n-π* electron transition of C–O bonds (non-bonding oxygen states) (He et al., 2018; Williams et al., 1983). Fig. 1
                         demonstrates the UV–visible absorption and emission spectra of NCQDs, (a, b) HASHP, (c, d) HASHNH3, and (e, f) HASHEDA.

According to the cytotoxicity assay results, the samples diluted at a ratio of 1:1000 did not display any harmful effects on the DLD1 cells. The pseudoviron assay using S protein pseudotyping showed an overall efficiency of 18–22% when using the Td tomato platform. In the control group, which did not contain any test samples, approximately 20% of the cells exhibited fluorescence. Comparatively, the sample HASHP and HASHNH3 displayed fluorescence in 3% and 4% of SARS-CoV-2 pseudoviron cells, respectively; symbolizing 85% and 80% of inhibition, when diluted in the ratio 1:1000 dilution, In case of HASHEDA samples indicated fluorescence in 5% of SARS-CoV-2 pseudoviron cells, indicating 75% inhibition when diluted in the same ratio of 1:1000. Hence, HASHP, HASHNH3 demonstrated slightly better inhibition of SARS-CoV-2 pseudoviron than HASHEDA samples in the SARS-CoV-2 pseudoviron when compared to control samples (Table 2
                        , Fig. 7
                        ).
